WEBVTT

00:00:00.000 --> 00:00:09.000
From the Library of Congress and the Smithsonian National Museum of African American History and Culture.

00:00:09.000 --> 00:00:12.000
Okay, okay, all right. Well, here we are.

00:00:12.000 --> 00:00:18.000
All right, so this is Emilye Crosby on December 4th, 2015.

00:00:18.000 --> 00:00:26.000
And I'm here with Mr. James Miller, Ms. Carolyn Miller at Mississippi Cultural Crossroads in Port Gibson, Mississippi.

00:00:26.000 --> 00:00:36.000
We're here with the Civil Rights History Project, which is Crosby sponsored by the Library of Congress and the Smithsonian National Museum of African American History and Culture.

00:00:36.000 --> 00:00:43.000
And with us, our John Bishop and Guha Shankar. And good morning. Thank you for joining us.

00:00:43.000 --> 00:00:44.000
Good morning.

00:00:44.000 --> 00:00:45.000
Good, Dr. Crosby.

00:00:45.000 --> 00:00:54.000
Could you tell us about men and where you were born and growing up when you can start and then?

00:00:54.000 --> 00:00:55.000
No, no, no.

00:00:55.000 --> 00:01:12.000
Well, I was born, actually at Alcorn State University now, but I was born in the infirmary at Alcorn State University then back in 1953,

00:01:12.000 --> 00:01:22.000
because back doing the 50s and before, there were only midwives.

00:01:22.000 --> 00:01:30.000
And my mother was having a difficult pregnancy. And my grandmother, who was an educator in the community,

00:01:30.000 --> 00:01:38.000
she had a little pool and she was able to get my mom down to the infirmary.

00:01:38.000 --> 00:01:51.000
So I was born there. I was the only one in my family actually born in the hospital, so to speak, or with a professional medical person.

00:01:51.000 --> 00:01:53.000
Thank you, brothers and sisters.

00:01:53.000 --> 00:01:59.000
They were born by midwives. I was the first, so I gave her a little trouble.

00:01:59.000 --> 00:02:01.000
That was the only time.

00:02:01.000 --> 00:02:08.000
In terms of midwives, Ms. Dismute was a pretty bad midwife in this community.

00:02:08.000 --> 00:02:10.000
Ms. Dismute.

00:02:10.000 --> 00:02:11.000
Jessie?

00:02:11.000 --> 00:02:12.000
Jessie.

00:02:12.000 --> 00:02:13.000
Yes, Jessie.

00:02:13.000 --> 00:02:16.000
She brought me here.

00:02:16.000 --> 00:02:18.000
Is that her claim to fame?

00:02:18.000 --> 00:02:19.000
Yes.

00:02:19.000 --> 00:02:20.000
Yes.

00:02:21.000 --> 00:02:26.000
Who am I going to close?

00:02:26.000 --> 00:02:29.000
She was a beautiful midwife.

00:02:29.000 --> 00:02:31.000
So I was like, I don't know, unfortunately.

00:02:31.000 --> 00:02:33.000
Right. I was playing.

00:02:33.000 --> 00:02:34.000
Wow.

00:02:34.000 --> 00:02:41.000
But Ms. Dismute probably, everybody in the 50s, she was D1.

00:02:41.000 --> 00:02:45.000
She delivered a lot of babies.

00:02:45.000 --> 00:02:48.000
Did she just deliver babies for black families?

00:02:48.000 --> 00:02:51.000
Or did any white families go to a...

00:02:51.000 --> 00:02:52.000
I'm not sure about that.

00:02:52.000 --> 00:02:55.000
But I bet she probably did.

00:02:55.000 --> 00:02:56.000
Yeah.

00:02:56.000 --> 00:02:58.000
Poor black families.

00:02:58.000 --> 00:03:00.000
I'm the poor black families.

00:03:00.000 --> 00:03:01.000
Yeah.

00:03:01.000 --> 00:03:02.000
I probably did.

00:03:02.000 --> 00:03:05.000
But I was born here in Florida.

00:03:05.000 --> 00:03:08.000
And I was a...

00:03:08.000 --> 00:03:11.000
But that was a sheer problem.

00:03:11.000 --> 00:03:12.000
I was a...

00:03:12.000 --> 00:03:13.000
I don't...

00:03:13.000 --> 00:03:14.000
Grand Guff was talking about that earlier.

00:03:14.000 --> 00:03:15.000
Okay.

00:03:15.000 --> 00:03:17.000
Well, I'm born out there with.

00:03:17.000 --> 00:03:18.000
And it was...

00:03:18.000 --> 00:03:24.000
Growing up in the 50s and poor kids Mississippi.

00:03:24.000 --> 00:03:28.000
I was just running around campus.

00:03:28.000 --> 00:03:29.000
I didn't...

00:03:29.000 --> 00:03:32.000
I felt like, you know, happy.

00:03:32.000 --> 00:03:34.000
It was a little kid growing up here, right?

00:03:34.000 --> 00:03:36.000
And then all of a sudden things changed.

00:03:36.000 --> 00:03:37.000
You know?

00:03:37.000 --> 00:03:38.000
I don't know.

00:03:38.000 --> 00:03:43.000
I was like, it's the right movement showed up.

00:03:43.000 --> 00:03:46.000
And so you had something to focus on.

00:03:46.000 --> 00:03:47.000
Right?

00:03:47.000 --> 00:03:48.000
That was different.

00:03:48.000 --> 00:03:51.000
And it caused the way society was structured.

00:03:51.000 --> 00:03:53.000
You know, white folks said everything.

00:03:53.000 --> 00:03:54.000
Right?

00:03:54.000 --> 00:03:56.000
Black folks didn't have nothing to run around.

00:03:56.000 --> 00:04:04.000
In a lot of cases, you know, living, serving two kind of existence, trying to support their families.

00:04:04.000 --> 00:04:06.000
And so it was...

00:04:06.000 --> 00:04:07.000
Crazy.

00:04:07.000 --> 00:04:10.000
It was a crazy existence.

00:04:10.000 --> 00:04:12.000
And there was some crazy relationships.

00:04:12.000 --> 00:04:14.000
I mean, black folks and white folks.

00:04:14.000 --> 00:04:16.000
You know, I don't think you're talking about a lot, right?

00:04:16.000 --> 00:04:17.000
Okay.

00:04:17.000 --> 00:04:18.000
Yeah, that was a lot of progress.

00:04:18.000 --> 00:04:21.000
Obviously racism was going on too, right?

00:04:21.000 --> 00:04:27.000
But poor blacks and poor whites and a lot of cases built coalitions in the community, right?

00:04:27.000 --> 00:04:28.000
They supported each other since...

00:04:28.000 --> 00:04:29.000
They supported each other's family.

00:04:29.000 --> 00:04:32.000
And I think that was kind of like behind the singing kind of thing.

00:04:32.000 --> 00:04:35.000
You know, one-on-one kind of relationships, you know?

00:04:35.000 --> 00:04:37.000
Not no group dynamics.

00:04:37.000 --> 00:04:38.000
But still separate.

00:04:38.000 --> 00:04:39.000
And apart.

00:04:39.000 --> 00:04:46.000
Can you give an example of how that might work, either with people or just an example of what it would have been like, how that would work?

00:04:46.000 --> 00:04:49.000
Well, like my own man, right?

00:04:49.000 --> 00:04:50.000
Okay.

00:04:50.000 --> 00:04:53.000
I'm just saying, the share in the community, right?

00:04:53.000 --> 00:04:54.000
Okay.

00:04:54.000 --> 00:04:57.000
My father was a World War II veteran.

00:04:57.000 --> 00:05:02.000
And so he saw a lot of stuff when he went over on the European theater.

00:05:02.000 --> 00:05:05.000
And when he came back home, man, he talked a little bit about it.

00:05:05.000 --> 00:05:08.000
So it kind of opened up our eyes and stuff, right?

00:05:08.000 --> 00:05:11.000
And so some reason other poppers already smoothed.

00:05:11.000 --> 00:05:14.000
You know, he would have hairpuff laughing and going on stuff.

00:05:14.000 --> 00:05:17.000
So him and his dad had a pretty close relationship.

00:05:17.000 --> 00:05:20.000
And he would help pop from time to time.

00:05:20.000 --> 00:05:21.000
Okay.

00:05:21.000 --> 00:05:23.000
And give him a little money and some stuff, right?

00:05:23.000 --> 00:05:24.000
Besides paying him.

00:05:24.000 --> 00:05:29.000
I remember when one instance in particular, when I was at an all-corn.

00:05:29.000 --> 00:05:31.000
And they were wondering about how I was going to get to school, right?

00:05:31.000 --> 00:05:34.000
But I got a little fellowship, but I still needed some money.

00:05:34.000 --> 00:05:36.000
I was there, gave him pop the money.

00:05:36.000 --> 00:05:40.000
And then pop came to me and said, it looked boy, you know, it was dad giving me this, right?

00:05:40.000 --> 00:05:44.000
And then when that happened, right, the movement came.

00:05:44.000 --> 00:05:49.000
So you got some dynamics going on, right, between pop and me and dad.

00:05:49.000 --> 00:05:50.000
That was just thinking.

00:05:50.000 --> 00:05:51.000
You see what I'm saying?

00:05:51.000 --> 00:05:52.000
Yeah.

00:05:52.000 --> 00:05:54.000
I mean, those kind of things, right?

00:05:54.000 --> 00:05:56.000
And so, but pop never scold me.

00:05:56.000 --> 00:05:58.000
He never said, boy, don't be in the movement.

00:05:58.000 --> 00:06:00.000
He never said that.

00:06:00.000 --> 00:06:07.000
And so, I know this dad called pop in and do almost times about me running around here throwing

00:06:07.000 --> 00:06:12.000
bricks and stuff, you know, marching and doing all the kind of stuff in the movement, right?

00:06:12.000 --> 00:06:19.000
And because those kind of relationships, some black men head with other white men of authority

00:06:19.000 --> 00:06:20.000
in the community, right?

00:06:20.000 --> 00:06:25.000
It was a paternal kind of relationship, but that was a little bit of respect there too, you know what I'm saying?

00:06:26.000 --> 00:06:31.000
So you were just talking about how when you get ready to go to Alcorn, Dan McKay, who is the share of KG,

00:06:31.000 --> 00:06:38.000
dad, some money to help you go to Alcorn because they had a working relationship and at the same time,

00:06:38.000 --> 00:06:41.000
you're in the movement in the case trying to control you in the movement.

00:06:41.000 --> 00:06:42.000
Yeah.

00:06:42.000 --> 00:06:48.000
I think what it says too, you know, around my kind of way too is that black men back in the time,

00:06:48.000 --> 00:06:53.000
order to try to support their families, they had to jump through a lot of different kinds of hoops and stuff,

00:06:53.000 --> 00:07:00.000
you know, and make a lot of psychological, you know, trade-offs, okay, with a manhood, you know,

00:07:00.000 --> 00:07:03.000
compromise a lot on their manhood and stuff, right?

00:07:03.000 --> 00:07:08.000
Order for a father to family, I think, you know, pop was a good example of that, okay?

00:07:08.000 --> 00:07:14.000
And in English, that's one of those, the only other one I would mention very quickly is my head did the same thing,

00:07:14.000 --> 00:07:16.000
did a, because pop worked for him too.

00:07:16.000 --> 00:07:22.000
And my head was one of the supervisors and leaders in the community, right?

00:07:22.000 --> 00:07:29.000
And so pop had that kind of relationship with a lot of powerful white men in this community back in the day, okay?

00:07:29.000 --> 00:07:35.000
You know, you know, and about ten months, a slight out of switch, and I think too,

00:07:35.000 --> 00:07:38.000
it has to do with class, right, in the community, right?

00:07:38.000 --> 00:07:43.000
Because he probably was not, you know, what was the right word?

00:07:43.000 --> 00:07:49.000
He went out the bush, one said, you know, okay, he was like a sort of earth kind of person, okay?

00:07:49.000 --> 00:07:54.000
Shia Krupp, then you had the educators in the community, black educators, right?

00:07:54.000 --> 00:08:01.000
And at that time, business leaders too, because we had thriving black businesses in the community, right?

00:08:01.000 --> 00:08:06.000
So there was a middle class, a thriving black middle class that existed in the community, right?

00:08:06.000 --> 00:08:11.000
That powerful white folks for the most part interacted with, okay?

00:08:11.000 --> 00:08:17.000
Do you think their interactions with that sort of elite class, like the teachers, the ministers, the business leaders?

00:08:17.000 --> 00:08:21.000
Is that going to be a different kind of relationship from the one that they have with somebody like your father?

00:08:21.000 --> 00:08:24.000
No, they know primarily because he works for them, right?

00:08:24.000 --> 00:08:27.000
And they can rely on another worker?

00:08:27.000 --> 00:08:35.000
I think the relationship between the middle class and white at that time was hypocritical.

00:08:35.000 --> 00:08:41.000
They were trading off each other, they were struggling each other, he goes to a large group.

00:08:41.000 --> 00:08:48.000
But I think the relationship between, say, you know, pop and some of the pop-up white folks that he dealt with,

00:08:48.000 --> 00:08:50.000
I think it was more honest, honestly, you know?

00:08:50.000 --> 00:08:56.000
It was like, okay, well, it was just, there was a human interaction.

00:08:56.000 --> 00:09:00.000
It was paternalistic for sure, you know?

00:09:00.000 --> 00:09:02.000
But I think it was more genuine.

00:09:02.000 --> 00:09:11.000
So I remember interviewing Mr. Mott Hegli, and he talked about actually being out in the fields with the people that were working in this land.

00:09:11.000 --> 00:09:16.000
So that they actually have a chance to interact with each other outside, okay?

00:09:16.000 --> 00:09:22.000
I'm trying to, I'm a black educator and I'm trying to get money for the school, so I'm thinking what you want me to say, kind of thing.

00:09:22.000 --> 00:09:28.000
But they had their hands and everything, they were like school board members, they were like merchants, right?

00:09:28.000 --> 00:09:30.000
They were in the banks, you see what I'm saying?

00:09:30.000 --> 00:09:34.000
You know, and they were elected officials, it was all interwoven.

00:09:34.000 --> 00:09:36.000
You're talking about the black leadership?

00:09:36.000 --> 00:09:38.000
Yeah, the leadership.

00:09:38.000 --> 00:09:40.000
The white leadership.

00:09:40.000 --> 00:09:42.000
Yeah, the white leadership, right?

00:09:42.000 --> 00:09:49.000
And so that's why when the blacks and local, local, they're like George and they put on the boycott,

00:09:49.000 --> 00:09:54.000
and their argument was, okay, why are you boycotting the merchants?

00:09:54.000 --> 00:09:58.000
And got nothing to do with the fact that black folk came vote.

00:09:58.000 --> 00:10:00.000
Would you push it?

00:10:00.000 --> 00:10:02.000
Thought they all went in the same.

00:10:02.000 --> 00:10:08.000
The same people who were running, okay, city hall, and over here in the courthouse,

00:10:08.000 --> 00:10:13.000
were the same people who were on the school board, okay, who ran the businesses, you know what I'm saying?

00:10:13.000 --> 00:10:21.000
So that's the boycott that started in 66, and it was a whole list of demands there.

00:10:21.000 --> 00:10:27.000
And some of the merchants said we got nothing to do with this white boycott, and that's what we had for the good.

00:10:27.000 --> 00:10:29.000
Him and the men.

00:10:29.000 --> 00:10:32.000
He wasn't outrageous, Mr. and Mrs.

00:10:32.000 --> 00:10:37.000
We come and we shop in the business, put somebody in here to work, they look like me.

00:10:37.000 --> 00:10:41.000
You know, when you say Mr. and Mrs. what are you talking about?

00:10:41.000 --> 00:10:44.000
Mr. and Mrs. Whoever the last name is, the first name, Mr. and Mrs.

00:10:44.000 --> 00:10:46.000
You know, when you address me.

00:10:46.000 --> 00:10:53.000
When we went in the store, it was boy girl, as opposed to calling it by your name,

00:10:53.000 --> 00:11:01.000
or referring to kids working the white kids working in the store,

00:11:01.000 --> 00:11:10.000
referred to my grandmother, for example, as girl, as opposed to Mrs. Terransey.

00:11:10.000 --> 00:11:12.000
It was just respect.

00:11:12.000 --> 00:11:15.000
Basically, lack of respect.

00:11:15.000 --> 00:11:18.000
So can you both tell me a little bit more about your childhood growing up?

00:11:18.000 --> 00:11:22.000
You mentioned that you felt like really free, a carefree as a kid,

00:11:22.000 --> 00:11:26.000
and did you both go up in the country?

00:11:26.000 --> 00:11:34.000
I grew up in Hermanville, and my growing up was a little bit different from James,

00:11:34.000 --> 00:11:39.000
because I guess my family was considered a bourgeoisie saying,

00:11:39.000 --> 00:11:48.000
my grandmother was a school teacher, and my dad was in the Army,

00:11:48.000 --> 00:11:50.000
so he was a Korean veteran.

00:11:50.000 --> 00:11:58.000
And because my mom and dad were young, my grandmother decided,

00:11:58.000 --> 00:12:04.000
well, that was being transferred to different bases,

00:12:04.000 --> 00:12:10.000
and she decided, well, you guys are not going to take care with you.

00:12:10.000 --> 00:12:13.000
She will stay here because she's got to go to school,

00:12:13.000 --> 00:12:18.000
like, wouldn't we school other places, but anyway,

00:12:18.000 --> 00:12:23.000
I ended up living with my grandparents, my dad's parents raised me,

00:12:23.000 --> 00:12:30.000
and my grandmother's school teacher in Hermanville, for many years,

00:12:30.000 --> 00:12:35.000
and my grandfather was a big farmer, and he had his own,

00:12:35.000 --> 00:12:43.000
we had about 300, 800 kids of land, and he had workers on the property of black people.

00:12:43.000 --> 00:12:47.000
So they had a sort of different relationship,

00:12:47.000 --> 00:12:50.000
I guess the relationship like with James was explained,

00:12:50.000 --> 00:12:55.000
and it was because they were educated and had money,

00:12:55.000 --> 00:13:00.000
they were treated a little bit different than maybe Pops was,

00:13:00.000 --> 00:13:04.000
my father-in-law was.

00:13:04.000 --> 00:13:11.000
I think it was respect, but not mutual respect, respect for the fact

00:13:11.000 --> 00:13:17.000
that they did have an education, and that they had my grandfather,

00:13:17.000 --> 00:13:23.000
actually, he did not go to college, but he made it on his own.

00:13:23.000 --> 00:13:30.000
And he acquired all of this just from hard work.

00:13:30.000 --> 00:13:38.000
My growing up was a little bit different because everything we needed was on the farm.

00:13:38.000 --> 00:13:42.000
We ate from there, we ate everything from there.

00:13:42.000 --> 00:13:49.000
The only time we came into town to buy from the stores was to get furniture,

00:13:49.000 --> 00:13:55.000
sometimes sometimes we bought stables like meal,

00:13:55.000 --> 00:14:01.000
things like that, but I had an uncle who was right down the road who actually had his own meal.

00:14:01.000 --> 00:14:06.000
We didn't have to do that very much, very often.

00:14:06.000 --> 00:14:11.000
Neighbors were like a mile from you, or two miles,

00:14:11.000 --> 00:14:14.000
so it wasn't like everybody was right there together,

00:14:14.000 --> 00:14:18.000
so we played right there on our farm.

00:14:18.000 --> 00:14:21.000
But once we got...

00:14:21.000 --> 00:14:25.000
I never had any interaction with any white children.

00:14:25.000 --> 00:14:33.000
Actually, the only time I saw any was on school bus going through by the house.

00:14:33.000 --> 00:14:37.000
Did you think about the fact that they were going to a different school?

00:14:37.000 --> 00:14:39.000
At that time, no.

00:14:39.000 --> 00:14:44.000
I had no sense of what was going on because I was kind of sheltered.

00:14:44.000 --> 00:14:49.000
But my grandmother always taught me that I was just as good as anybody else.

00:14:49.000 --> 00:14:54.000
And then I didn't have to worry about that.

00:14:54.000 --> 00:14:58.000
I was a lot of people who told me,

00:14:58.000 --> 00:15:01.000
I'm referring to you and saw that as a bitch,

00:15:01.000 --> 00:15:05.000
because I have very self-confidence,

00:15:05.000 --> 00:15:10.000
so I don't worry about what other people think about me.

00:15:10.000 --> 00:15:15.000
And growing up,

00:15:15.000 --> 00:15:18.000
I had a lot of responsibility as the oldest.

00:15:18.000 --> 00:15:25.000
And my grandfather always told me that you're going to acquire all of this stuff

00:15:25.000 --> 00:15:28.000
once we're dead and gone,

00:15:28.000 --> 00:15:31.000
which didn't work out that way,

00:15:31.000 --> 00:15:34.000
because of other reasons.

00:15:34.000 --> 00:15:41.000
But they expected a lot of me and I tried to live up to that.

00:15:41.000 --> 00:15:47.000
And I never actually played with any white kids,

00:15:47.000 --> 00:15:51.000
anybody other than family or someone,

00:15:51.000 --> 00:15:55.000
some of the people who worked for my grandfather, they all children,

00:15:55.000 --> 00:15:58.000
and when I went to her middle school,

00:15:58.000 --> 00:16:02.000
I went to her middle school from first to sixth grade,

00:16:02.000 --> 00:16:06.000
and then I didn't have kindergarten made then,

00:16:06.000 --> 00:16:11.000
and then we'd have to come to court Gibson to go to middle school.

00:16:11.000 --> 00:16:19.000
And that's when things started to happen here in the county,

00:16:19.000 --> 00:16:24.000
the civil rights movement started, you know, began.

00:16:24.000 --> 00:16:27.000
It was once that year when we moved,

00:16:27.000 --> 00:16:31.000
when I started riding the bus to court Gibson to school.

00:16:31.000 --> 00:16:35.000
And then my dad and mom separated,

00:16:35.000 --> 00:16:38.000
and I got moved to court Gibson.

00:16:38.000 --> 00:16:42.000
So that's how I got involved.

00:16:45.000 --> 00:16:49.000
Did either of your parents try to register to vote when you were young

00:16:49.000 --> 00:16:53.000
before the movement started or talk about voting?

00:16:53.000 --> 00:16:57.000
No, my parents didn't.

00:16:57.000 --> 00:17:01.000
My mother was not a radical,

00:17:01.000 --> 00:17:04.000
she was kind of laid back, you know,

00:17:04.000 --> 00:17:06.000
and I always try to make peace.

00:17:06.000 --> 00:17:08.000
People get along and I say,

00:17:08.000 --> 00:17:11.000
you know, but she never discouraged us from not being radical.

00:17:11.000 --> 00:17:13.000
You know, it was three of us, right?

00:17:13.000 --> 00:17:16.000
Dawn, you know, me and Lois.

